BEST DUTCH OVEN CHICKEN RECIPE
made at my parent’s house using their special pot.

Why should you make this?
1. All you need is 1 pot - little mess.
2. The flavor is incredible.
3. Super healthy. Recipes like this keep us in shape without sacrificing flavor.

If you want to save recipe cards - go to my Dutch Oven highlights.

Tag someone who would like this dish!

1 whole organic chicken, 4 lb.
2 sweet potatoes, peeled and chopped
1/2 butternut squash, peeled and cubed
1 fennel, chopped
1/2 onion chopped
salt & pepper to season
4-6 fresh sage leaves, chopped
3 sprigs or rosemary, chopped
(I also use both these herbs to stuff cavity)
extra virgin olive oil
1 cup chicken stock (optional)
1/2 cup white wine (optional)

1. Clean the chicken and pat dry with paper towels. Let sit at room temp for 30 minutes before roasting. 

2. Pre-heat oven to 425 F.

3. Add the sweet potatoes, squash, fennel (including their stems) and onion to a dutch oven pot. Season generously with salt and pepper. 

4. Add the sage and rosemary. Stuff some in the cavity of the chicken.

5. Season the chicken with salt and pepper on all  sides. Massage olive oil all over the chicken - and carefully get some under the skin without breaking it.  Place chicken on top of veggies. 

6. Cover pot and cook in oven for 50 minutes.

7. Remove dutch oven cover. I added 1 cup of chicken stock and 1/2 cup white wine and mixed it in. Cook uncovered for another 30 minutes.

8.  Remove from oven. Put chicken on a cutting board and let rest for 15 minutes. Strain Vegetables from dutch oven and reserve the delicious liquid for gravy.

9. Serve with the veggies under the chicken and pour some gravy on top. I also added a salad for some extra green and crunch! 

This is healthy comfort food!

FRENCH WOMEN DON’T GET FAT
The Secret of Eating for Pleasure

By Mirielle Guiliano

When I was in high school, I did not eat pasta. I know…can you imagine?! I thought pasta was the enemy, and I was lucky if the scale would ever break 100 pounds. I was obsessed with dieting and exercise, and my life was all about discipline, deprivation and deducing calories. I was no fun to be around, and this was NOT the life for The Chef’s Daughter who was always exposed to some of the best French and Italian food NYC had to offer.

And so, I picked up this book and read it twice: “FRENCH WOMEN DON’T GET FAT”
The Secret of Eating for Pleasure -  By Mirielle Guiliano

I fell in love with Mirelle’s wisdom and finally stopped my dieting nonsense. She recommended taking the stairs instead of an elevator any chance you could get and I was running up staircases all over Manhattan - in stilettos. This was about the time I started being more mindful about creating a lifestyle I would want to live forever. I became fascinated by how the French and the Italians lived and I started imitating them. The good news is:  we do have a choice in how we do life, and I chose to bring pasta back into mine!

I posted some of my favorite quotes from this book. Scroll through them and see if one resonates with you. They have had a profound influence on the lifestyle I live today.

Many of you ask me: “Do I eat the Pasta I make!” Yes, and it is because I created a lifestyle that always allows me to include my favorite things in life. If working out is not your jam, then take the stairs and walk as much as possible!

For me, life should and must be enjoyed. 
What is your philosophy on life?

SPAGHETTI SQUASH LASAGNA
Craving something comforting, tasty and satisfying!
Here it is!  Keto friendly and Gluten Free

Serves 2
INGREDIENTS

•1 medium spaghetti squash
•        salt and freshly ground pepper, to season
•        extra virgin olive oil
•        8oz Italian chicken sausage, sliced
•        1/2 onion, finely chopped
•        1/2 can crushed tomatoes
•        fresh basil leaves
•        2 garlic cloves, chopped
•4 tbsp grated parmesan cheese
•1 tbsp chopped parsley, or basil
•3/4 cup whole milk shredded mozzarella cheese

INSTRUCTIONS
•Preheat oven to 375ºF.
•Slice spaghetti squash in half lengthwise and remove the seeds and the membrane.  Season generously with salt and black pepper.  Drizzle olive oil on top and bake until it is soft, about 1 hour and 15 minutes.
•While the spaghetti squash bakes, prepare the filling. In a medium sauté pan, heat oil over high heat and brown the chicken sausage, breaking it up into small crumbles until browned and cooked. 
•Add onions and cook until translucent and fragrant..
•Add the crushed tomatoes, basil and garlic.  Season with a little more salt and pepper. Simmer for 30 minutes uncovered.  Add some more fresh basil leaves at the end.
•Once the spaghetti squash is cooked, use a fork to remove flesh. This comes out looking like spaghetti strands.  Add the strands to the tomato sauce and mix until combined..
•When the spaghetti squash is cool enough to handle, use a fork to remove flesh, which will come out in spaghetti looking strands. Reserve the shells.
•Add the sauce and strands to the squash shells.  Sprinkle with the parmigiano regianno cheese and bake in the oven for 20 minutes more.
•Before serving, drizzle with a little more olive oil.  Sprinkle some more cheese on top and garnish with a basil leaf.  Enjoy.

A POT OF COMFORT:  BRAISED CHICKEN THIGHS with MUSHROOMS & FENNEL,

There are just some days that take you down, and that we have no control over. However, we can always find some joy on these dark days with a little comfort food - like this recipe. I completely improvised it and even cried a little while cutting my shallots (sometimes, you need to let it all out). It is a 1 pot recipe because I had NO energy to clean after, but it was delicious, healthy and soothing.  I hope you give it a try.

Recipe cards in dutch oven highlights 😘

Serves (2-4)

Ingredients

5 chicken thighs, skin on
salt and pepper, to season
extra virgin olive oil
3 cups white mushrooms, quartered
1 fennel bulb, chopped - including the stem and fronds
4 shallots, diced
1/2 cup white wine (I only had red and I made it work)
1 14.5 oz can of diced tomatoes
1 cup chicken stock
fresh sage leaves, torn
a few sprigs of thyme, removed from stem
1 big handful of arugula

Directions

1. Clean the chicken thighs and then pat dry.  Season on both sides with salt and pepper.

2.  Heat oil in a dutch oven pot. Once hot, add chicken and brown on both sides until golden (about 5 minutes each). Remove from pot and set aside.

3.  Add mushrooms to pot and cook for 5-7 minutes.

4.  Meanwhile, chop your fennel and dice the shallots.  Add to the pot and cook for 5 minutes more.

5.  Add wine and bring to a boil.  Allow the wine to reduce by half, while scraping any brown bits on the bottom up with a wooden spoon. This is where the flavor lies.

6.  Add tomatoes and stock, and bring to a boil.

7.  Reduce to a simmer.  Add fresh herbs and return chicken to the pot. Cover with lid and simmer for 15-20 minutes.

8.  Remove the lid and add arugula.  Season with salt and pepper.  Cover for 2 minutes more.

9.  Serve with some of the juice from the pot. This tastes even better the next day.

Buon Appetito

Last week I lost my CHOCOLATE BROWN PRADA BOOTS. I started thinking of all the hotels I could have possibly left them in. I went to my friend’s house searching through her closet in hopes they would be there. I called my mother several times having her check her house - hoping she would find them. 

What was the stress over these boots all about?

I received these boots 12 years ago when my life was all about hustling in my theater for 16 hours a day (sometimes 7 days a week). Prada boots were something this single divorcee playwright and director could not even imagine owning. Yet, I spent days in my dusty theater sweats- dreaming of Italian fashion and would often buy Vogue magazine over dinner - (I know, I watched too much Sex and The City.) And then one day, just like that I received these Prada, suede, chocolate, knee length, 6 1/2 - $1600 boots as a gift from someone who had so much money that the price tag didn’t even put a dent in his account. My first reaction was I better return them, because my Hollywood rent was $1700 and I killed myself to pay it. But I had to keep them, and I promised my boots that I would take care of them so I could wear them forever.

The loss of these boots reminded me of where my last journey started.

 I started my thirties financially depleted after an unfortunate divorce set me back. So, one day I picked up this book by ― Malcolm Gladwell, Outliers: The Story of Success and read it twice. Scroll through this post to read some of its quotes. 

Those Prada boots were a symbol of where I started when life was crumbling around me, and I needed to pick my distraught butt up to make something happen. I was alone in LA and did not have 1 good friend by my side at this point. So, the quotes from this book kept me going, and were something I lived by.  And the Prada boots, well they served as a consistent reminder of how I wanted things that were extraordinary, and needed to create a life to get them.

PS: yay! my mom texted me this morning with a picture of my chocolate brown - 12 year old- prada boots.They are going to be on my feet in NYC next week while I take my last steps in 2022!

To COMPARE or To Have COMPASSION - that is the question.

This post is for anyone who is been caught in the Comparison Web! I, The Chef’s Daughter, have been in an unhealthy state of comparing myself physically to others in the past few weeks. My fitness minded friends are inspirational women with gorgeous bodies. Lately, I have been comparing mine to theirs,  and here is why this is toxic:

1.My body is different. My age is different and I am going through things that are specific to me. How could I possibly compare myself to other bodies who are not enduring the same things mine is?

2. When we do this, we are left feeling not good enough - less than. I was behaving in a way where I felt that I needed to do better, despite some of the things I am going through that could prevent me from feeling my best. This is a no win situation I put myself in.

3.  By comparing ourselves to others, we are negating our own road. I was negating mine. I was resisting it.

On my way to the vet today, my dog was shaking. She always does when we go to the vet. Somehow, she knows when we are going there - it is a super power she possesses. I changed my energy in the car - put on soft music and began telling her a story of the past 13 years we have had together. Skype calmed down in a way I never saw her do before. This shift in energy from Anxiety to Calmness completely changed her state in minutes. During that story, I realized the power I possessed to do the same for me. By listening to my own words in this calm voice, I started feeling a deep compassion for myself and everything I have endured recently. At that moment, I realized Compassion NOT Comparison is the shift I needed.

If you are comparing yourself to others, train yourself to STOP this habit and focus on Compassion for yourself instead. 

More about this to come, but if you needed to hear this post today - comment below.

And guess, what - when I am compassionate towards myself - I enjoy my Homemade Pasta without guilt. When I am comparing myself to others - I eliminate it and also give up joy.

What do you choose: COMPARISON or COMPASSION?

BRAISED CHICKEN THIGHS with LEEKS & MUSHROOMS

In the winter months, I find myself BRAISING often. Braising allows meats to tenderize and dramatically changes the flavor of otherwise bland food. It also keeps tough cuts of meat nice and moist.

If you are unfamiliar with BRAISING, I suggest you give it a try. It will allow your food to maintain its nutritional value, and it is an easy cooking technique that leaves little mess. You can also just throw the pot in the oven and get something else done. One last perk, just in case I have not convinced you yet, is that you can make braised dishes a day in advance -  because the left overs taste even better when the flavors have had time to come together.

Give this clean eating recipe a try! 

INGREDIENTS
4-5 Chicken Thighs, with skin
1 leek coarsely chopped, white part only
extra virgin olive oil, (as much as needed)
salt and freshly ground pepper, to season

MIGNONTETTE MARSALA:  Filet Mignon in a Marsala Wine Sauce

Would you like to learn how to make this succulent preparation of beef, which will delight even the most devout carnivores?
Then get ready to open our cookbook: “The Chef of Greenwich Village” to page 220, or purchase it at our link so you too can create a masterful culinary dish like this.

One of the main ingredients in this dish is Marsala wine, a fortified wine from Sicily. It is the Marsala that gives the sauce its nutty richness. Chef Pietro will not trust a bottle of Marsala wine that’s made anywhere but Sicily. Additionally, the Chef instructs that the size of the mignonette is very important. He prefers to use a 1/3 pound fillet. When asked why, my father replies, “You don’t want the cut too small as they have a tendency to cook quickly, and if that happens, it is difficult to achieve medium rare filet.”

On the day I learned how to prepare my father’s mignonette, Chef Pietro remarked with a smirk, as he plated his impressive dish and garnished it with parsley,

“What’s the matter with you La-La-Land (another nickname he has given me); you want to cook, but then you don’t eat the food?”

He then prepared himself a plate of his Mignonette Marsala, forgetting that I was monitoring his eating (red meat is not exactly on his coronary artery disease diet). I compromised with my father and allowed him to have one big bite, and then I grabbed the plate and put the rest of the mignonette in a to-go box for my mother. I do not enjoy these moments and I feel like the strict daughter, but I guess this is what tough love looks like! Do not feel too bad for him though, as Chef Pietro still gets an allowance to indulge in his signature meat dishes, but these moments are now reserved for special occasions.

Cut out a paper ❤️ and fill it with something healthy and yummy for a romantic, healthy and simple dinner.  Sea Bass with Tomato & Lentils prepared in parchment paper can be prepared in advance and then when ready to eat, throw it in the oven and enjoy the beautiful aromas that come from the bag.

Ingredients 
(Serves 2)

1 lb. sea bass filet, skin removed
salt and pepper, to season
1 cup steamed lentils 
1 cup grapes tomatoes, halved
2 garlic clove, sliced
1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil 
6 fresh basil leaves, torn 
6 stalks fresh oregano stalks

Preparation and Cooking Instructions

 1,  Cut out a ❤️ using parchment paper measuring 18-20 inches.  Lay the paper flat down on table to the side and reserve for Assembly.

2. Season the bass with salt and pepper on both sides, drizzle a little oil on each filet, both sides.  Set aside.

3. Season the lentils with salt and pepper.  Drizzle a little oil on top and mix together.  Set aside.

4. Season the tomatoes and garlic with salt and pepper.  Drizzle a little oil in and mix together.  Throw in torn basil and mix together. Set aside.

 5. On the left half the heart, spread some lentils. Add the fish on top. Then, top the fish with  the tomatoes.

6. Seal the parchment heart by bringing the right side of the heart to meet the left side. Seal it by pressing down on your fingers.  Then double fold it to make sure it stays closed.

7. Place on a baking sheet and cook for 20 minutes.
 Remove from the oven and place each packets on a plate.  Have your guests open this at the table for an impressive presentation and start to your dinner. Everyone at the table will feel special with this little package to open!

The Key to Success in the Kitchen is… MISE EN PLACE! 

MISE EN PLACE:  pronounced, MEEZ ahn plas, which simple means- “putting in place”. Try to not let this fancy French term intimidate you, as the concept is simple and when mastered, can not only change your experience in the kitchen, but in can transform other areas of your life as well.  For now, we will stick to what Mise En Place means in the culinary world.  In professional kitchens it is extremely important for a chef to organize and arrange their ingredients in an orderly fashion in order to be successful. 

 Here is how to set up a professional mise en place: 

-  Gather all the tools you will need for your recipe.  Make sure all your knives are sharp and clean.  Keep them together in a jar or a sheet pan where they can be easily accessed.

- Place your cutting board in the center of your workspace.  Be sure it is secured and cannot move.  You can either wet a cloth or put some liner underneath the board to keep it in it’s place.  This is very important to do in order to avoid getting hurt. 

- Next, take three large empty bowls.  One should be placed on the center of your cutting board.  The other two bowls should be above the cutting board, one on the left hand corner and the other to the right.  The left bowl should contain all the vegetables you will be using.  These vegetables are in their natural state.  The right side bowl should contain any vegetables that have been peeled and cored, and are now ready to be chopped.  The middle bowl will serve as a trash bowl.  Therefore, you can peel and core all your vegetables over the bowl, keeping your workspace clean and manageable.  Note:  It is recommended to first peel and core all your vegetables per recipe, before you begin cutting, chopping or dicing…etc.

THE SECRET YOU HAVE ALL BEEN WAITING FOR: SALMORIGLIO 

Enjoy this incredible  Olive Oil, Lemon and Herb Marinade
Drizzle a little sauce and accentuate the flavor.

This recipe is one of my favorite secrets to being FIT and SATISFIED.   When you buy a very high quality fresh fish and combine it with this ancient Sicilian marinade, you have a restaurant quality meal that is so delicious and healthy, you will crave it over and over again. You can use Salmoriglio on any type of grilled fish meat or vegetable, so experiment with it. I love serving this sauce with swordfish too. The best part is that it is very quick to make, so whip some up and pass this vibrant condiment around the table. I even like to smear it on some toasted bread. 

INGREDIENTS

For the Salmoriglio
6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
3 tablespoons hot water
2 lemons, juiced
1 tablespoon garlic, minced
1 tablespoon fresh Italian parsley, chopped
1 tablespoon fresh oregano, chopped
sea salt and freshly pepper, to season

PREPARATION:

Pour the olive oil into a pot over simmering water. Whisk in the water and lemon juice until they gently simmer.

Add the lemon, garlic, parsley and oregano and simmer for 3-5 minutes, continuing to whisk.
Season to taste with salt and pepper and remove sauce from the simmer water and set aside.

Drizzle the Salmoriglio sauce on top and enjoy!
You are so worth this yummy, healthy marinade!

I am going to explore my Body Story some more today. This is a conversation we are having within our Brooke Burke Body Community @brookeburkebody and I feel inspired by women sharing!

This is my story - I am a woman who is finally becoming comfortable in her own skin. When I was a teenager - I would not be caught dead in a bikini. I was a little late to bloom, unlike a lot of the other girls in my high school. And then, finally - right before I turned 16 - my body started developing and I was humiliated by it. I experienced something at one of my best friend’s Sweet 16 parties - and it all occurred when I got called up to light a candle. A bunch of boys started chanting - “Chest, Chest, Chest” at me. You see, my dress was showing cleavage for the first time and the boys noticed right away. I was horrified and wanted to figure out a way to use scissors to get rid of my chest. Yes, their chanting caused me so much shame.

So… I became the girl at the beach with a one piece bathing suit on who was always crossing my arms to protect my body. I was so self conscious and could not imagine ever feeling free in a bikini. When I became aware that a world noticed your body and wasn’t afraid to vocalize it - I wanted to hide mine.

So… what would I tell that almost 16 year old girl today?

1. Quit being polite! If someone says something rude and insensitive - call them out on it. Don’t silently take it in! No one deserves to point out things on your body - Period! 

2. Fight back against intimidation by standing up for others - especially yourself! 

3. Be a risk taker - you want to wear a bikini and feel good in it, then do not hold back! 

4. Our thoughts are not always are most helpful allies. If your thoughts are critical because of what someone said - change the inner dialogue to a nurturing tone. If our thoughts are fearful - keeping us from showing who we are to the world and causing us to hold back - switch them to a playful voice.

5. Don’t not do something because you are worried about what others will say - people will always talk anyway - so let that go and do what feels right and authentic for you!

SPRING LEEK SOUP with Chicken & Cannellini Beans

Once again,pre-made chicken can really relieve the dinner-rush pressure-especially in this Malibu Italian-inspired Spring soup that will leave you feeling nourished this season,

Ingredient Checklist
	•	2 teaspoons extra-virgin olive oil 
	•	2 leeks, white and light green parts only, cut into 1/4-inch rounds 
	•	1 tablespoon chopped fresh sage, or 1/4 teaspoon dried 
	•	3 parsnips, peeled and chopped
	•	24 ounces homemade chicken broth (see previous recipe or DM me)
	•	2 cups water 
	•	Salt and pepper to season
	•	1 15-ounce can cannellini beans, rinsed 
	•	4 cups shredded chicken, saved from homemade chicken broth. 
	•	Fresh Parsley to garnish

Note: If you do not make your own broth, purchase low sodium and then buy a premade rotisserie chicken.

Directions

	•	Drizzle the oil into a dutch oven and sauté the leeks until fragrant.  Throw in the sage and continue cooking until fragrant, about 30 seconds. 
	•	Add the parsnips and continue to stir.
	•	Pour  in broth and water, increase heat to high and bring to a boil.
	•	Season with salt and pepper and simmer for 30 minutes
	•	 Add beans and chicken and cook, uncovered, stirring occasionally, until heated through, about 3 minutes. 
	•	Serve hot.
	•	Garnish with Fresh Parsley  
Tips
Make Ahead Tip: Cover and refrigerate for up to 2 days.

How to Make Bagna Cauda, by Chef Giovanni …AKA - Amore Mio!

ATTENTION …
 CALLING ALL GARLIC LOVERS! ❤️

Bagna Càuda, literally translated as “hot bath, is a dipping sauce for veggies that is very easy to make. When garlic, anchovies and liquid gold, extra virgin olive oil melt together - an aromatic, heavenly, rich sauce is born!
Serve this with veggies and toasted bread. You can also serve it over polenta, salad, pasta or scrambled eggs.

Serves 6

INGREDIENTS
6 heads of garlic
1 1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
3 ounces anchovies
1/2 espresso cup of cream.

INSTRUCTIONS
	1.	Peel the garlic and chop finely.
	2.	Add half the olive oil and garlic to a small pot and simmer slowly over low heat.
	3.	Rinse the anchovies, dry them and add to the pot. Use a wooden spoon to mix and watch them dissolve into the oil. Your kitchen will smell amazing!
	4.	Add the rest of the oil and simmer for 20 minutes. 
	5.	Pour in the cream, mix with wooden spoon and simmer for 5 minutes more.
	6.	Drizzle the bagna cauda into a terrine, and serve alongside some raw veggies and bread.

ASPARAGUS SPRING SOUP
Serves 4-6

If you are craving a healthy, seasonal and delicious SOUP - here it is!
Give this a try - you are so WORTH IT! Tag a friend who would love this ASPARAGUS SOUP!

INGREDIENTS:

extra virgin olive oil 
1 onion, chopped
1/2 leek, only white part- chopped 
3 parsnips, peeled and chopped
2 bunches of asparagus, chopped
2 1/2 cups  homemade chicken broth 
2 cups water
1 large thyme sprig
1 1/4 teaspoons salt
1/4 teaspoon freshly ground white pepper

DIRECTIONS:

Drizze some olive oil in a cast iron pot and heat.
Add the onions & leeks, and  cook until transulcent and fragrant.
Add the parsnips and continue to cook 5 minutes more.
Add the asparagus, broth and water. 
Bring to a boil and then reduce to a simmer.
Add thyme and season with salt and pepper.
Let the soup simmer for 30 minutes. Then, take it off the heat and blend together. I like using an immersion blender.
Serve immediately, or refrigerate up to 3-5 days

*If you do not have homemade chicken broth, use store bought.

MY SECRET TO LIFE: BALANCING SELF DISCIPLINE WITH INDULGENCE!

Can we have self control & yet indulge all at the same time?
I SAY YES WE CAN!

To indulge means -  to allow oneself to enjoy the pleasure of.

Those of us in the fitness world can find this concept hard - as our self discipline can intrude on our pleasure and distract us from enjoying some of life’s greatest pleasures.
Also, self control leads to great outcomes - doesn’t it? It keeps us aligned with our long - term goals, such as weight loss.

But can we have too much self-control? Can our self control limit our pleasure?

Did you know that people who are living happy and satisfied lives fill their days with pleasurable experiences free from guilt?

	When they do something, they are fully immersed in it!
 
Think of how important it is to experience pleasure when
 - you dine w/friends & family
 - you enjoy a view
 - you engage in intimacy with your lover
 - you walk barefoot on sand
 - you move with intention 
 - you sip a glass of wine
 - you soak up the sun on an Italian beachside.
	…and so much more!

Pleasure and satisfaction are important to our mental health!

Do you feel freedom wearing a bathing suit?

If not, I want to invite you into a conversation I am very passionate about - Body Freedom! I have a dear friend who is working out so hard and her body looks strong and fit. I communicated that to her yesterday, and she replied that she wishes to feel good in a bikini, but doesn’t. That breaks my heart, because so many of us are so hard on ourselves and we think we need to be “perfect” to feel body freedom.

Here is a little story of why I am the perfect person to help you with this freedom…
I once was with my friend’s husband who almost crashed his car when I was in it. I hit my head hard, and instead of apologizing to me and making sure I was okay - this jerk said, “ I was hoping to crash so that you could have finally gotten that nose job you always needed.” Yup… but before you go on and hate him too much - that same man is now serving a prison sentence for being a criminal and swindling money from his friends. I hope he is reflecting on that moment from jail! Today,  I am now so thankful for his words. Why? Well because I cried my eyes out when I got out of the car, and took his words to heart! A newly single woman in LA - alone without family, barely making ends meat as a theatre artist did not need to hear that - especially since she just had a head injury and did not have good health insurance to get it checked. However, his words pushed me to find the beauty in myself despite how much power I gave them. This took work, as words can really hurt us! But Guess what? I am Italian 🇮🇹 - I love my imperfect nose, and Sophia Loren also heard comments about her nose and look how she owned it and radiated with confidence. 💋

Feeling confident and free in a swimsuit has so much more to do with looking perfect! To me, it has all to do with acceptance, and not listening to all the jerks out there that made you feel bad about your looks and body. Lock them up in your own jail, and live free! So what if something on you is not perfect … I think it it is still beautiful! 

My wish is that my friend puts on a bathing suit, feels free in it and enjoys all the hard work she has put in at the gym!

CHILLED OVERNIGHT OATS

Who is looking for a heart friendly vitamin filled breakfast that will not only make you feel full, but will satisfy you with it’s delicious, creamy pudding like consistency, and also help you burn more Fat?  I know, we all are!  Overnight Oats has become my new breakfast choice.  I love waking up in the morning, grabbing my spoon, pulling my mason jar out of the fridge and having an instant meal that I look forward to.  My recipe below is filled with nutrients. 

 One of the advantages between chilling the oats versus heating them up, is they quadruple in volume rather than vanish in the heat.  So, you feel like you are eating more, even though you are not!  The best part of this recipe is you can make 5 at a time, chill them and have them Monday thru Friday to get you through the week without anymore mess or fuss!  OVERNIGHT OATS IS THE MEAL WE SHOULD ALL BE EATING.  It is even Gluten Free!

Serves 1

1/2 cup rolled oats
1 cup almond milk
1 tablespoon crushed walnuts
1 tablespoon sliced almonds
1 tablespoon sunflower seeds
2 tablespoons chia seeds
1 teaspoon cinnamon
1 tablespoon almond butter
1 cup almond milk
4-5 strawberries, chopped

In a mason jar, or any closed container, place the rolled oats.  Drizzle a drop of the milk in.  Add the walnuts, almonds, sunflower seeds, chia seeds, cinnamon and almond butter.  Pour the rest of the milk in.  Add the strawberries on top, or any fruit of choice.
Place in the refrigerator and soak over night.

Enjoy a quick and easy recipe in the morning.

Okay, let me share a memorable experience from my culinary journey. It all happened just two weeks after I graduated from culinary school, when I was brimming with enthusiasm and a thirst for knowledge. At that time, an amazing opportunity came knocking at my door.

I came across a remarkable woman, whom I’ll refer to as LA SIGNORA, hailing from Bari -  in the Puglia region of Italy. She had set up her own delightful cake business in the elegant neighborhood of Carol Gardens, Brooklyn. And guess what? She was searching for someone to assist her in creating authentic Italian cakes - a field I had yet to explore. Despite my lack of expertise, the job description seemed like a dream come true.

To my surprise, LA SIGNORA discerned my potential from just reading my cover letter. Perhaps it was my recent graduation from culinary school or the fact that I am proud to be the daughter of the renowned Chef Pietro Mosconi, who skillfully manages two of New York City’s bustling restaurants. Either way, she saw something special in me, and I felt like I had struck gold in her eyes.

As soon as I stepped into her kitchen, the enchanting process of cake-making began. La Signora had an impressive display of eight kitchen mixers humming in harmony. It was a sight I had never witnessed before, as I had only used such a device once in my life. She effortlessly created many  traditional, rustic Italian cakes. Although I felt sluggish in keeping up with her, I gradually found my rhythm while attempting to replicate her signature recipes. I dreamt of spending the summer by La Signora’s side but alas, my dream was abruptly shattered. La Signora confessed that she enjoyed my company but criticized my cake-making skills, humorously declaring me the worst she had ever encountered (gotta love the straightforward Italians). She even questioned my lineage as Chef Pietro’s daughter. A single tear welled up in my eye, yet deep down, I empathized with her assessment.

And guess what?  Through countless hours of practice and experimentation, I can now whip up these delectable treats almost as quickly as La Signora herself. True mastery comes from experience - thank you La Signora! 🙏🏻❤️

Get ready to elevate your taste buds with a burst of fresh, light, and vibrant flavors in this impressive recipe for Tuna Tartare. 🐟🥑🍋
#TunaTartare #FreshAndDelicious
Ingredients (Serves 4-6):
    •     2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
    •     2 tablespoons olive oil
    •     1 teaspoon peeled and minced fresh ginger
    •     3 green onions, finely chopped
    •     1 lb. sushi-grade tuna fillet, cut into small cubes
    •     Pinch of sea salt
    •     1 tablespoon soy sauce, preferably reduced sodium
    •     1 1/2 tablespoons sesame oil
    •     1 tablespoon honey
    •     2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice, divided
    •     1 avocado, finely chopped
    •     2 tablespoons of cilantro, finely chopped
    •     1/2 Persian cucumber, diced finely
    •     Salt and pepper to season (if desired)
Preparation:
    1     Prepare the tuna: Remove any skin or sinew from the tuna fillet. Using a sharp knife, dice the tuna into 1/4 inch cubes. Set aside.
    2     Toast the sesame seeds: In a small, dry pan, toast the sesame seeds until golden brown (2-3 minutes). Be vigilant while toasting to avoid burning.
    3     In a mixing bowl, combine the toasted sesame seeds, olive oil, ginger, green onions, soy sauce, sesame oil, honey, and 1 tablespoon of lemon juice.
    4     Add the diced tuna to the bowl and gently mix to combine.
    5     In a separate mixing bowl, combine the chopped avocado, cilantro, cucumber, remaining lemon juice, and season with salt and pepper (if desired). Stir gently to combine.
    6     To plate, use a mold and pack the avocado and cucumber mixture first. Then, layer the tuna tartare on top.
    7     Garnish with a pinch of sesame seeds.
    8     Carefully remove the mold and serve immediately.
    9     Enjoy with rice crackers or try serving the tartare on endive leaves.

* Feel free to double the recipe as you need.

Brew the espresso

Grilled veggies are the ultimate star of any Malibu Italian feast, and here’s how we do it:

Ingredients:

  2 bulbs fennel, sliced vertically into 1/2 inch thick slices
  1 head radicchio, separated into leaves
  2 zucchini, sliced lengthwise 1/3 inch thick slices
  2 eggplant, sliced lengthwise 1/2 inch thick slices
  3 -4 shallots , sliced vertically into 1/2 inch thick slices
  6 Portobello mushrooms, sliced
  1 bunch (1-pound) asparagus, trimmed
  1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil, plus 3 tablespoons

  1 garlic clove, minced

4️⃣ In a small bowl, mix the remaining 3 tablespoons of olive oil, balsamic vinegar, shallot, garlic, and chopped herbs.

🍯 Balsamic Honey Glazed Pork Tenderloin with Roasted Veggies 🥕🥦🍠
Ingredients:
	•	1 lb pork tenderloin
	•	Salt and Pepper
	•	1 tbsp Olive Oil
	•	1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
	•	2 tbsp honey
	•	1 tbsp Dijon mustard
	•	2 sweet potatoes, peeled and chopped
	•	1 butternut squash, peeled and chopped
	•	3 beets, peeled and chopped
	•	1 parsnip, peeled and chopped
	•	1/2 red onion, sliced
	•	2 cups Brussels sprouts, halved
	•	Extra virgin olive oil
	•	Salt and Pepper
Directions:
	1.	Marinate the Pork: Place pork tenderloin in a bag, add salt, pepper, olive oil, balsamic vinegar, honey, and Dijon mustard. Seal the bag and let it marinate for 30 minutes.
	2.	Preheat the Oven: Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C).
	3.	Prepare the Veggies: On a sheet pan, arrange sweet potatoes, butternut squash, beets, parsnip, red onion, and Brussels sprouts.
	4.	Season and Drizzle: Sprinkle the veggies with salt, pepper, and a drizzle of extra virgin olive oil.
	5.	Roast the Veggies: Roast the veggies in the preheated oven for 25 minutes, turning them over halfway through.
	6.	Add the Pork: After 25 minutes, add the marinated pork tenderloin to the sheet pan with the veggies.
	7.	Finish Roasting: Continue roasting for an additional 15-20 minutes or until the pork reaches an internal temperature of 145°F (63°C).
	8.	Serve: Slice the pork tenderloin and serve it alongside the beautifully roasted vegetables.
	9.	Enjoy: Time to savor this real and delicious meal! 🍽️✨

One of the crown jewels of Italian cuisine, Linguine Vongole, takes on a mythical dimension when conjured by the hands of my esteemed father, the illustrious Chef Pietro. 
A fundamental tenet of dolce far niente, as any discerning Italian will attest, is the sacred decree to never taint this dish with even a whisper of cheese. I find great amusement in observing the theatrical disdain exhibited by the Italian waiters at Monte’s Trattoria when an unsuspecting patron dares to request a sprinkle of cheese on their Linguine with Clams. To the Italian sensibility, this act borders on criminal transgression. Gastronomically speaking, their revulsion holds true - the introduction of cheese would irreversibly overwhelm and alter the delicate essence of the clams and their luscious sauce.
So, dear connoisseurs of Italian fare, embrace the essence of being Italian - relish this pasta unadulterated by any form of cheese!

INGREDIENTS (Serves 4)
1 pound of Linguine
1/2 cup of the finest extra virgin olive oil
2 tablespoons of finely chopped garlic (approximately 6 cloves)
4 dozen Manila clams in their proud shells (in the absence of Manila clams, little neck or cherry stone clams serve as worthy alternatives)
3 tablespoons of freshly chopped Italian parsley
2 stalks of enchanting oregano
1/2 cup of cool, revitalizing water
A pinch of crushed red pepper to awaken the senses

PREPARATION AND COOKING INSTRUCTIONS
Boil salted water and cook linguine until just shy of recommended time.
Infuse olive oil with garlic until it turns a golden hue, avoiding over-browning.
Add clams, parsley, oregano, and a drizzle of water to balance saltiness.
Cover and cook clams, removing unyielding shells.
Combine linguine, parsley, and red pepper with clams for 1½ minutes.
Plate the dish, ensuring no oregano stalks remain. Optionally garnish with remaining parsley.

Embark on a holiday flavor journey with our Stuffed Artichoke Hearts! 🌟 Simmered in garlicky olive oil, sprinkled with Parmigiano Reggiano, and baked to perfection – a festive feast that captures the essence of the season. ✨ Elevate your holiday table with this family tradition! 🍽️ 

Ingredients:
1 can of artichoke hearts, drained and halved
1/4 cup olive oil
3 cloves garlic, minced
1 cup Parmigiano Reggiano, grated
1 cup breadcrumbs
Salt and pepper to taste
Fresh parsley for garnish (optional)

Instructions:
1. Preheat your oven to 350°F (175°C).
2. In a skillet, heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add the minced garlic and sauté until fragrant, ensuring not to brown the garlic.
3. Slice the artichoke hearts in half and arrange them in a baking tray.
4. Drizzle the garlicky olive oil over the artichoke hearts.
5. Sprinkle half of the Parmigiano Reggiano over the artichokes, ensuring an even distribution.
6. In a separate bowl, combine the breadcrumbs with the remaining Parmigiano Reggiano. Add a pinch of salt and pepper to taste.
7. Slowly drizzle some of the olive oil from the garlic mixture into the breadcrumb and cheese mix. Stir until it forms a paste-like consistency.
Carefully spoon the breadcrumb mixture over the artichoke hearts, ensuring each one is generously coated.
8. Bake in the preheated oven for 20-25 minutes or until the tops are golden brown and the artichokes are heated through.
9. Remove from the oven and let them cool slightly before serving.
10. Garnish with fresh parsley if desired.
Serve these delightful Stuffed Artichoke Hearts as a flavorful appetizer or a side dish, perfect for adding a touch of elegance to your holiday table.

Roasted Brussels Sprouts with Hazelnuts, Fresh Orange, Brown Butter, and Basil

Elevate your Brussels sprouts experience with our tantalizing recipe. Sensually halved, roasted to perfection, and adorned with hazelnuts, fresh orange, brown butter, and a whisper of dried basil. A symphony of sophistication awaits.

Ingredients:

1 lb Brussels sprouts, halved and ends trimmed
2 tbsp olive oil
Salt and pepper to taste
1 cup hazelnuts, finely chopped
Zest of 1 orange (shaved into 2-3 pieces)
3-4 tbsp unsalted butter
Juice of 1 fresh orange
1/2 tsp dried basil
1/4 cup pomegranate seeds (optional, for garnish)
Directions:

Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C).
Toss halved Brussels sprouts with olive oil, salt, and pepper. Roast for 15-20 minutes until golden and crispy.
In a pan, toast hazelnuts and orange zest until fragrant. Discard the orange zest.
In a separate saucepan, brown butter, and add dried basil for an aromatic touch. Stir in fresh orange juice until the butter browns again.
Pour the brown butter and basil sauce over the roasted Brussels sprouts.
Sprinkle finely chopped hazelnuts over the dish, ensuring an even distribution.
Optionally, garnish with pomegranate seeds for a burst of color and sweetness.
Serve immediately and succumb to the seduction of Roasted Brussels Sprouts with Hazelnuts, Fresh Orange, Brown Butter, and Basil.

VEAL (VITELLO) SALTIMBOCCA 🍽️✨

Chef Pietro’s quick, tasty, and elegant dish is a classic requested at @Montestrattoria and @Villamosconi. Saltimbocca, translating to “jump in the mouth,” ensures a flavorful experience! If you’re not buying pre-pounded veal scaloppini, channel your inner Italian chef and do it yourself. Chef Pietro does it with eyes closed—Italian style! Where would you find this dish in Italy? Rome, of course!

📚 Featured in tastecooking.com and my cookbook “The Chef of Greenwich Village.”

  24 sage leaves
  4 TBSP extra virgin olive oil
  4 TBSP butter
  4 bay leaves
  All-purpose flour for coating
